01:00:35.430 --> 01:00:42.190
The phase difference delta will
be equal to, of course, pi.

01:00:42.190 --> 01:00:49.560
This pi contribution is coming
from the flip of the amplitude.

01:00:49.560 --> 01:00:53.810
That will actually give
you an pi phase difference.

01:00:53.810 --> 01:00:58.140
The second phase difference
is coming from the difference

01:00:58.140 --> 01:01:01.900
in the optical path length.

01:01:01.900 --> 01:01:07.140
You can see that the first path,
it doesn't go into the film.

01:01:07.140 --> 01:01:10.270
It got reflected, directly.

01:01:10.270 --> 01:01:15.300
And the second path,
which is path number two,

01:01:15.300 --> 01:01:20.120
it takes more
effort or more time

01:01:20.120 --> 01:01:23.740
for the light to go
back and reach your eye.

01:01:23.740 --> 01:01:27.320
How big is the path
length difference?

01:01:27.320 --> 01:01:33.030
The size of the path length
difference is 2 times d, right?

01:01:36.540 --> 01:01:40.500
Of course, I need to
actually translate that back

01:01:40.500 --> 01:01:45.330
to the phase.

01:01:45.330 --> 01:01:49.020
So first, I need to actually
