01:17:22.390 --> 01:17:24.750
YEN-JIE LEE: It's white, right?

01:17:24.750 --> 01:17:29.610
Remember, because of
the optical setup,

01:17:29.610 --> 01:17:33.440
this image is
actually upside down.

01:17:33.440 --> 01:17:39.190
So the upper edge of
that image is actually

01:17:39.190 --> 01:17:43.990
the lower edge of
my setup, which is

01:17:43.990 --> 01:17:46.295
the lower edge of my soap film.

01:17:51.830 --> 01:17:55.390
We have gravity, right,
so that I can walk around.

01:17:55.390 --> 01:18:02.514
Due to gravity,
you can see that it

01:18:02.514 --> 01:18:06.160
will form a thicker
and thicker layer

01:18:06.160 --> 01:18:09.700
in the bottom of my
experimental setup

01:18:09.700 --> 01:18:13.720
or in the upper
edge of the image.

01:18:13.720 --> 01:18:16.490
On the other hand,
due to gravity,

01:18:16.490 --> 01:18:21.700
the upper edge or the
lower edge of the image

01:18:21.700 --> 01:18:26.060
will become thinner and
thinner as a function of time.

01:18:26.060 --> 01:18:31.840
At some point, the color
will start to show up.

01:18:31.840 --> 01:18:39.270
As you can see now, since
we wait long enough,

01:18:39.270 --> 01:18:41.950
the soap film becomes
thinner and thinner.

01:18:41.950 --> 01:18:46.011
And you can see that there
are colors popping up.

01:18:46.011 --> 01:18:47.910
It's like a rainbow.

01:18:47.910 --> 01:18:48.610
Why is that?

01:18:48.610 --> 01:18:54.020
Because I am varying the
thickness of the film

01:18:54.020 --> 01:18:58.180
as a function of the
vertical distance.

01:18:58.180 --> 01:19:01.160
So therefore, you can see that
this is actually showing you

01:19:01.160 --> 01:19:07.760
that different d value will
give you very different colors.

01:19:07.760 --> 01:19:10.900
And if we wait long
enough, basically what

01:19:10.900 --> 01:19:15.730
we are going to get is
that the whole film will

01:19:15.730 --> 01:19:18.850
become more and more colorful.

01:19:18.850 --> 01:19:21.520
And I am sure that
after this class,

01:19:21.520 --> 01:19:23.140
you can walk out
of the classroom

01:19:23.140 --> 01:19:29.320
and explain to your friend why
the soap bubble is colorful.

01:19:29.320 --> 01:19:30.530
Thank you very much.

01:19:30.530 --> 01:19:34.480
And if you have any
questions, I will be around.

01:19:34.480 --> 01:19:37.750
And of course, if you want
to make your own soap bubble,

01:19:37.750 --> 01:19:40.610
you can actually go ahead
and play the demo here.

01:19:48.310 --> 01:19:49.870
So hello, everybody.

01:19:49.870 --> 01:19:54.250
So we are going to show
you a demonstration, which

01:19:54.250 --> 01:20:00.060
we can see colorful interference
pattern from a soap film.

01:20:00.060 --> 01:20:04.270
So basically, the experimental
setup up is like this.

01:20:04.270 --> 01:20:06.040
Basically, we have
light, which is

01:20:06.040 --> 01:20:11.710
trying to shine this
thin layer of soap film.

01:20:11.710 --> 01:20:17.030
And the result is actually
projected on the screen.

01:20:17.030 --> 01:20:20.170
And you can see, at
first, you don't really

01:20:20.170 --> 01:20:26.640
see a lot of colorful
pattern, because the thickness

01:20:26.640 --> 01:20:33.430
of the film is still
rather large, rather thick.

01:20:33.430 --> 01:20:36.060
Therefore, you don't really
see a lot of pattern.

01:20:36.060 --> 01:20:38.560
But as a function
of time, you can

01:20:38.560 --> 01:20:40.960
see that this pattern
is actually changing.

01:20:40.960 --> 01:20:46.220
Because of
gravitational force, you

01:20:46.220 --> 01:20:51.940
will be able to see that
the lower part of the film

01:20:51.940 --> 01:20:53.740
becomes thicker and thicker.

01:20:53.740 --> 01:20:58.540
And the upper part of the film,
which you see that upside down

01:20:58.540 --> 01:21:03.490
on the screen, is actually
becoming thinner and thinner.

01:21:03.490 --> 01:21:08.530
As we actually discussed during
the class, when soap film is

01:21:08.530 --> 01:21:16.375
thin enough, there will be
only one or only a few maximas

01:21:16.375 --> 01:21:23.500
in the interference pattern
as a function of wavelengths,

01:21:23.500 --> 01:21:28.600
which happened to be inside
the visible light range.

01:21:28.600 --> 01:21:32.910
And you can see it now,
already, this colorful pattern

01:21:32.910 --> 01:21:33.820
really develops.

01:21:33.820 --> 01:21:35.470
It's really beautiful.

01:21:35.470 --> 01:21:42.620
And you can see that, in the
lower part of the experiment,

01:21:42.620 --> 01:21:45.280
really have authentic
color, because there

01:21:45.280 --> 01:21:51.260
are multiple maximas in
the visible light range.

01:21:51.260 --> 01:21:55.400
On the other hand, in the
upper part of the film,

01:21:55.400 --> 01:21:59.800
you typically have very
little number of maximas

01:21:59.800 --> 01:22:04.430
or only have one maxima,
in the visible light range,

01:22:04.430 --> 01:22:06.110
as a function of wavelength.

01:22:06.110 --> 01:22:08.570
Therefore, you see
really, really dramatic

01:22:08.570 --> 01:22:14.310
and very, very colorful pattern
develop from this experiment.

